<br>
How many mobs is VI going to have to &quot;nerf&quot; in order to make up the gap that not having rod2/full CH is going to create?  What about buff time?  How long will it take VI to implement those changes?  Hell, how many broken mobs are there in the game RIGHT NOW that VI hasn't gotten around to fixing?<br>
<br>
Seems to me (and I could be wrong /shrug) that the only people this truly plays into the hands of are folks who are so bloody well equipped that they no longer require these rod2 mana tactics to buff for or run a high end encounter.  And the irony is that they all used that tactic to get themselves all that equipment.  Guilds running behind that level of FT/HP's/DPS from weaponry/ etc. ad nauseum..., now lack an important tool that keeps such equipment even farther out of their reach.  The funny thing is that several high end mages ASKED for it!  Congratulations to everyone who whined about not wanting to be a rod vending machine.  And my sincerest condolences to those who did not.  Manaburn?  BFD.  VI nerfed it properly IMHO.  But the damage caused by the immediate changes to how CH and rods work will fundamentally change the way that high end encounters will work.   I'm wondering what VI's theoretical target solution is...to increase the number of people necessary to take down a mob thereby increasing lag?  Seriously, how many folks do you want to take on AoW?  What will the lack of this mana source do to your buff time?  How is this shortening an encounter?  *sigh*  In essence, I agree with the original poster of this thread.  Anyone who has ever relied upon a mod rod to expedite the encounter process just took one between the cheeks.<br>
